package org.nodriver4j.scripts;

import org.nodriver4j.core.Page;
import org.nodriver4j.persistence.entity.ProfileEntity;
import org.nodriver4j.services.*;


import java.util.Scanner;

public class GoogleDocs implements AutomationScript {

    // ==================== Form Selectors ====================

    private static final String[] CONTENT = {"\"Fair is foul, and foul is fair; / Hover through the fog and filthy air.\"", "Act 1, Scene 1, Lines 79-80", "Imagery - The witches close the opening scene with fog and filthy air, establishing a world in which moral clarity is obscured from the start. The blurred atmosphere signals that the play's Scotland will be a place where good and evil become indistinguishable, and darkness serves as the natural element of those who trade in deception.", "\"but signs of nobleness, like stars, shall shine / On all deservers.\"", "Act 1, Scene 4, Lines 533-534", "Simile - Duncan compares noble worthiness to shining stars, associating light with legitimate authority, honor, and merit. This association is immediately inverted when Macbeth, in his next speech, asks those same stars to hide their fires, revealing how the usurper seeks to extinguish the very symbols of virtue the rightful king celebrates.", "\"Stars, hide your fires; / Let not light see my black and deep desires. / The eye wink at the hand, yet let that be / Which the eye fears, when it is done, to see.\"", "Act 1, Scene 4, Lines 548-551", "Apostrophe and imagery - Macbeth directly addresses the stars, commanding darkness to conceal his murderous ambition. By personifying light as a witness to guilt and asking it to look away, Macbeth reveals that he understands his desires are morally corrupt and can only be pursued under the cover of concealment.", "\"Come, thick night, / And pall thee in the dunnest smoke of hell, / That my keen knife see not the wound it makes, / Nor heaven peep through the blanket of the dark / To cry 'Hold, hold!'\"", "Act 1, Scene 5, Lines 632-636", "Personification and imagery - Lady Macbeth invokes night as a concealing shroud, asking darkness to hide the murder even from heaven's sight. The \"blanket of the dark\" metaphor treats darkness as a protective covering for evil, while her fear that heaven might \"peep through\" reveals an awareness that moral order cannot be permanently suppressed.", "\"O, never / Shall sun that morrow see!\"", "Act 1, Scene 5, Lines 654-655", "Metaphor - Lady Macbeth declares that Duncan will never see the next day's sun, equating extinguishing his life with the elimination of light. The sun here stands for life and the natural order that the Macbeths intend to destroy, foreshadowing Scotland's descent into figurative darkness under their rule.", "\"There's husbandry in heaven; / Their candles are all out.\"", "Act 2, Scene 1, Lines 879-880", "Metaphor - Banquo compares the stars to candles that have been extinguished, casting the night sky in total darkness on the eve of Duncan's murder. The word \"husbandry\" (thrift) implies heaven itself is conserving its light, as though the natural world is withdrawing its illumination in anticipation of the unnatural act about to occur.", "\"Now o'er the one-half world / Nature seems dead, and wicked dreams abuse / The curtained sleep. Witchcraft celebrates / Pale Hecate's off'rings, and withered murder, / ...towards his design / Moves like a ghost.\"", "Act 2, Scene 1, Lines 954-962", "Personification and imagery - Macbeth describes the night as a time when nature dies and evil reigns, personifying murder as a figure that stalks through the darkness like a ghost. The passage transforms nighttime from a simple absence of light into an active, malevolent force that enables wickedness, reflecting Macbeth's own surrender to the darkness he invoked in Act 1.", "\"By th' clock 'tis day, / And yet dark night strangles the traveling lamp. / Is 't night's predominance or the day's shame / That darkness does the face of earth entomb / When living light should kiss it?\"", "Act 2, Scene 4, Lines 1417-1421", "Personification and imagery - Ross describes how, on the morning after Duncan's murder, unnatural darkness has swallowed the sun. The verbs \"strangles\" and \"entomb\" personify darkness as a violent, suffocating force, while \"living light\" and \"kiss\" associate daylight with life and tenderness. The cosmic disruption mirrors the political one: regicide has thrown even the natural order of day and night into chaos.", "\"Come, seeling night, / Scarf up the tender eye of pitiful day / And with thy bloody and invisible hand / Cancel and tear to pieces that great bond / Which keeps me pale. Light thickens, and the crow / Makes wing to th' rooky wood. / Good things of day begin to droop and drowse, / Whiles night's black agents to their preys do rouse.\"", "Act 3, Scene 2, Lines 1806-1814", "Personification and imagery - Macbeth again invokes night as an active accomplice, asking it to blindfold (\"scarf up\") the eye of day so evil can proceed unseen. The phrase \"Light thickens\" captures the motif at its most compressed: light itself is becoming sluggish and opaque, as though Macbeth's tyranny is physically corrupting the atmosphere. The contrast between \"good things of day\" drooping while \"night's black agents\" rouse frames the play's moral landscape as a battlefield between light and darkness.", "\"Who did strike out the light?\"", "Act 3, Scene 3, Line 1876", "Symbolism - During the ambush on Banquo, the torch is extinguished, allowing Fleance to escape in the confusion of total darkness. On the literal level, the murdered light enables the son's survival; symbolically, the murderers' own darkness becomes an obstacle to completing Macbeth's plan. Evil's reliance on darkness proves to be both its instrument and its limitation, as the very concealment Macbeth requires also prevents the elimination of the prophesied threat.", "\"Angels are bright still, though the brightest fell. / Though all things foul would wear the brows of grace, / Yet grace must still look so.\"", "Act 4, Scene 3, Lines 2792-2795", "Allusion and imagery - Malcolm alludes to Lucifer (\"the brightest\" angel who fell) to explain why Macduff's apparent goodness cannot be taken at face value. The passage acknowledges that evil disguises itself in light, but insists that genuine virtue must continue to look like virtue regardless. This complicates the motif by showing that under Macbeth's tyranny, even light itself has become suspect, as moral appearance and moral reality can no longer be easily matched.", "\"The night is long that never finds the day.\"", "Act 4, Scene 3, Line 3138", "Metaphor - Malcolm closes the act with a proverb equating Scotland's suffering under tyranny with an endless night and liberation with the coming of day. This compact line reframes the entire light-and-darkness motif as a national condition: Macbeth's reign is the night, and the military campaign to restore Malcolm represents the dawn that Scotland desperately needs.", "\"She has light by her continually. 'Tis her command.\"", "Act 5, Scene 1, Lines 3183-3184", "Irony and symbolism - The Gentlewoman reveals that Lady Macbeth, who once invoked \"thick night\" and the \"dunnest smoke of hell\" to conceal murder, now insists on having a candle burning at all times. This reversal is the motif's most powerful moment: darkness, which she once summoned as an ally, has become the thing she fears most, because it now represents the guilt and horror she can no longer suppress. The shift from commanding darkness to desperately clinging to light dramatizes the unsustainability of evil's reliance on concealment.", "\"And all our yesterdays have lighted fools / The way to dusty death. Out, out, brief candle!\"", "Act 5, Scene 5, Lines 3537-3538", "Metaphor - In his final soliloquy, Macbeth reduces life to a \"brief candle\" and a \"walking shadow,\" collapsing the motif's two poles into a single image of futility. Light no longer represents goodness or truth; it merely illuminates the path to death. The command \"Out, out\" echoes Lady Macbeth's \"Out, damned spot,\" linking both characters' despair, and Macbeth's weariness of the sun (line 3578) confirms that he has exhausted both darkness and light as sources of meaning.", "\"All hail, Macbeth! Hail to thee, Thane of Glamis! / All hail, Macbeth! Hail to thee, Thane of Cawdor! / All hail, Macbeth, that shalt be king hereafter!\"", "Act 1, Scene 3, Lines 284-290", "Foreshadowing - The witches' three escalating titles form the seed of Macbeth's ambition, offering a trajectory from his current status to the throne. This prophecy functions as the catalyst of the entire tragedy, transforming a loyal subject into a man consumed by the possibility of kingship.", "\"If you can look into the seeds of time / And say which grain will grow and which will not, / Speak, then, to me, who neither beg nor fear / Your favors nor your hate.\"", "Act 1, Scene 3, Lines 300-303", "Metaphor - Banquo compares the witches' ability to see the future with an agricultural image, suggesting prophecy is like knowing which seeds will eventually sprout. His measured tone (\"neither beg nor fear\") contrasts sharply with Macbeth's startled reaction, establishing Banquo as a foil who approaches prophecy with rational caution rather than consuming ambition.", "\"Lesser than Macbeth and greater. / Not so happy, yet much happier. / Thou shalt get kings, though thou be none.\"", "Act 1, Scene 3, Lines 312-318", "Paradox - The witches' prophecy for Banquo is deliberately riddling, pairing opposites to suggest that fate operates in ways that defy straightforward interpretation. The prediction that Banquo will father kings without being one himself plants the seed of Macbeth's later paranoia, as the crown he seizes will ultimately pass to Banquo's descendants.", "\"And oftentimes, to win us to our harm, / The instruments of darkness tell us truths, / Win us with honest trifles, to betray 's / In deepest consequence.\"", "Act 1, Scene 3, Lines 415-418", "Metaphor - Banquo characterizes the witches as \"instruments of darkness\" that use truthful predictions as bait for a deeper betrayal. This warning functions as a thematic thesis for the prophecy motif: the danger lies not in the predictions themselves, but in how ambition causes the listener to interpret them as invitations to act.", "\"Two truths are told, / As happy prologues to the swelling act / Of the imperial theme.\"", "Act 1, Scene 3, Lines 421-423", "Dramatic irony - Macbeth interprets the two fulfilled prophecies as encouraging prologues to his kingship, using theatrical metaphor to cast himself as the destined hero of the story. The audience, informed by Banquo's warning moments earlier, recognizes that this \"supernatural soliciting\" may be leading Macbeth toward self-destruction rather than glory.", "\"I dreamt last night of the three Weird Sisters. / To you they have showed some truth.\"", "Act 2, Scene 1, Lines 907-908", "Foreshadowing - Banquo reveals that the witches' prophecy has invaded his subconscious, showing its psychological hold even on a character who consciously distrusts it. His acknowledgment that the prophecy \"showed some truth\" for Macbeth highlights how partial fulfillment lends the witches credibility, making their remaining predictions harder to dismiss and more dangerous to act on.", "\"Then 'tis most like / The sovereignty will fall upon Macbeth.\"", "Act 2, Scene 4, Lines 1467-1468", "Dramatic irony - Ross casually predicts that Macbeth will become king, unaware that this is exactly what the witches foretold and what Macbeth has murdered to achieve. The ease with which political logic arrives at the same conclusion as supernatural prophecy underscores the play's question of whether fate drives action or merely describes outcomes that ambition would have produced regardless.", "\"Then, prophet-like, / They hailed him father to a line of kings. / Upon my head they placed a fruitless crown / And put a barren scepter in my grip, / Thence to be wrenched with an unlineal hand, / No son of mine succeeding.\"", "Act 3, Scene 1, Lines 1600-1605", "Metaphor - Macbeth reinterprets the Banquo prophecy as a personal curse, calling his crown \"fruitless\" and his scepter \"barren\" because neither can produce a dynasty. The prophecy that was originally directed at Banquo now torments Macbeth more than his own prophecy ever inspired him, demonstrating how prophecy's power lies not in what it promises, but in what it denies.", "\"I will tomorrow / (And betimes I will) to the Weird Sisters. / More shall they speak, for now I am bent to know / By the worst means the worst.\"", "Act 3, Scene 4, Lines 2149-2152", "Dramatic irony - After the banquet's collapse, Macbeth resolves to seek the witches again, treating prophecy as a source of strategic intelligence. His phrase \"by the worst means the worst\" reveals that he has fully abandoned moral caution; the prophecies that once troubled his conscience are now tools he actively pursues, showing how the desire to control fate deepens one's dependence on the very forces that manipulate it.", "\"He shall spurn fate, scorn death, and bear / His hopes 'bove wisdom, grace, and fear. / And you all know, security / Is mortals' chiefest enemy.\"", "Act 3, Scene 5, Lines 2204-2207", "Foreshadowing - Hecate reveals that the witches' next set of prophecies will be designed to create overconfidence, making Macbeth \"spurn fate\" and feel invulnerable. This passage exposes the mechanism behind the entire prophecy motif: the witches do not simply predict the future but engineer a false sense of security that leads the victim to his destruction.", "\"Be bloody, bold, and resolute. Laugh to scorn / The power of man, for none of woman born / Shall harm Macbeth.\"", "Act 4, Scene 1, Lines 2450-2452", "Dramatic irony - The Second Apparition delivers a prophecy that appears to guarantee Macbeth's invincibility, since all humans are presumably born of women. The deception lies in the gap between Macbeth's assumption and the literal truth: Macduff was delivered by caesarean section and is therefore technically not \"of woman born.\" This is the play's clearest example of prophecy exploiting the distance between apparent and actual meaning.", "\"Macbeth shall never vanquished be until / Great Birnam Wood to high Dunsinane Hill / Shall come against him.\"", "Act 4, Scene 1, Lines 2474-2476", "Dramatic irony - The Third Apparition's prophecy seems to promise permanent safety, since a forest cannot uproot itself and march. Macbeth immediately dismisses the possibility (\"That will never be\"), illustrating exactly the overconfidence Hecate described. The prophecy will be fulfilled literally when Malcolm's soldiers camouflage themselves with cut branches, turning a seemingly impossible condition into a tactical reality.", "\"Thou art too like the spirit of Banquo. Down! / Thy crown does sear mine eyeballs... / What, will the line stretch out to th' crack of doom?\"", "Act 4, Scene 1, Lines 2512-2517", "Imagery and dramatic irony - The vision of eight kings descended from Banquo confirms the one prophecy Macbeth most wanted to defeat: that Banquo's line, not his, will inherit the throne. The image of the line stretching \"to th' crack of doom\" emphasizes the futility of Macbeth's crimes; no amount of murder can overwrite what fate has inscribed. The searing of his eyeballs by the crowns' brightness inverts the motif of light, as kingly radiance becomes a source of torment for the usurper.", "\"I pull in resolution and begin / To doubt th' equivocation of the fiend, / That lies like truth.\"", "Act 5, Scene 5, Lines 3571-3573", "Dramatic irony - When a messenger reports that Birnam Wood appears to move, Macbeth's absolute confidence in the prophecy cracks for the first time. His phrase \"lies like truth\" captures the essence of prophetic equivocation: the witches' predictions were technically accurate but designed to be misread. This moment marks the transition from false security to dawning recognition that he has been manipulated.", "\"Despair thy charm, / And let the angel whom thou still hast served / Tell thee Macduff was from his mother's womb / Untimely ripped.\"", "Act 5, Scene 8, Lines 3712-3715", "Dramatic irony and reversal - Macduff reveals the loophole in the \"none of woman born\" prophecy: he was delivered by caesarean section, making him technically unborn of woman. The prophecy is fulfilled in its precise, literal sense while destroying the interpretation Macbeth had built his confidence upon. This moment is the culmination of the prophecy motif, demonstrating that fate's language is exact but never transparent, and that seeking invulnerability through prophecy only ensures a more devastating fall.", "\"And be these juggling fiends no more believed / That palter with us in a double sense, / That keep the word of promise to our ear / And break it to our hope.\"", "Act 5, Scene 8, Lines 3720-3723", "Metaphor and anagnorisis - In his final speech about the witches, Macbeth arrives too late at the understanding Banquo offered in Act 1: the \"instruments of darkness\" use truth itself as a weapon. The phrase \"double sense\" names the mechanism of every prophecy in the play, as each prediction kept its literal \"word of promise\" while violating the meaning the listener assumed. Macbeth's recognition functions as the moral conclusion of the prophecy motif: seeking to control fate through foreknowledge leads only to self-destruction."};

    // ==================== Constructor ====================

    /**
     * No-arg constructor for {@link ScriptRegistry} factory.
     */
    public GoogleDocs() {
    }

    // ==================== AutomationScript Implementation ====================

    @Override
    public void run(Page page, ProfileEntity profile, TaskLogger logger,
                    TaskContext context) throws Exception {

        try (Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in)) {
            logger.log("Press Enter when ready...");
            scanner.nextLine();

            for (int step = 0; step < CONTENT.length; step++) {
                String input = scanner.nextLine().trim();

                if (input.equals("exit")) {
                    break;
                }

                if (!input.isEmpty()) {
                    try {
                        int index = Integer.parseInt(input);
                        if (index >= 0 && index < CONTENT.length) {
                            step = index;
                        }
                    } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
                        logger.log("Invalid input, continuing with step " + step);
                        // don't skip — fall through to type the current step
                    }
                }

                page.type(CONTENT[step], 1.5);
            }

            logger.success("Exited " + profile.emailAddress());
        } catch (RuntimeException e) {
            logger.error(e.getMessage());
        }

        throw new RuntimeException("Signup failed unexpectedly for: " + profile.emailAddress());
    }
}